<h2>What Eardogger is For</h2>

<p>Most bookmark tools are for <em>researching and indexing:</em> mark a specific page, and that mark stays put until you delete it.</p>

<p>But Eardogger is for <em>reading,</em> and a reader's bookmark is constantly moving. So instead of saving isolated pages, Eardogger saves your <em>position within a larger work.</em> You get one bookmark ("dogear") per site, and when you mark a new location on that site, it just updates the existing bookmark.</p>

<p>The upshot is that it only takes <em>one click</em> to save your place in a thing you've been reading, which adds up if you're working your way through a long webcomic (or fanfic, or technical manual) over the course of several weeks.</p>

<h2>How to use Eardogger</h2>

<ol>
  <li>On all your devices and browsers, bookmark the Eardogger homepage and install the "Mark my spot" and "Where was I" bookmarklets.</li>
  <li>To pause what you're reading, click "Mark my spot."
    <ul>
      <li>If it's a site you've dogeared before, that's it! The dogear now marks your new position.</li>
      <li>If it's a new site, it'll ask you for a name and then create a new dogear. (You can also adjust the URL prefix, for sites that share a domain with several other sites.)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>To resume reading a site from where you paused it, either:
    <ul>
      <li>Use the list of dogears on the <a href="/">Eardogger homepage</a>.</li>
      <li>If you're already on that site, click "Where was I." (Useful when you left a tab open, but it's behind your current position because you read further on another device.)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

